    en: "NY law bans smoking and vaping in most indoor workplaces. The rule is in NY Public Health Law sections 1399-n through 1399-x — the Clean Indoor Air Act, often called the Smoke-Free Air Act. The ban took effect in 2003 and was expanded in 2017 to include electronic cigarettes and vaping. Covered places include offices, retail stores, restaurants, bars, healthcare facilities, schools, and most other indoor workplaces. Limited exceptions include certain cigar bars, tobacco retail shops, and licensed hookah bars. The law covers an outdoor area within 100 feet of school entrances and certain hospital entrances. Employers must post no-smoking signs and enforce the ban. Penalties for violation run up to $2,000 per violation against the building owner or operator."
